   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page01.jpg"/>
            <p>	Thank you my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName> for your <del>kind</del><lb/>
               letter &amp; I am much obliged to you &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Lady Robinson</persName> for<lb/>
               your kind wish of seeing me at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cranford_ENK">Cranford</placeName>; if ever I<lb/>
               should go into that part of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>, which I fear<lb/>
               is highly improbable I should certainly not neglect<lb/>
               to pay my respects to her Ladyship or to renew my<lb/>
               acquaintance <hi rend="underline">in person</hi> with her agreeable <choice><orig>daugh-<lb/>
                  -ter </orig><reg>daughter</reg></choice>- I am going on though not with so much<lb/>
               alacrity with the work I have began, for the first<lb/>
               volume has been gone some time and we are afraid<lb/>
               as we have heard no news of it, that some accident<lb/>
               has befallen it - Alas it would be a woeful <unclear>mischanc</unclear><lb/>
               enough to discourage a poor scribbler at her first<lb/>
               setting out - however I shall begin the <unclear>third</unclear> <choice><orig>vo-<lb/>
                  -lume </orig><reg>volume</reg></choice>next week - how we are talking of<lb/>
               Books pray have you read a new work of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GenlS1"><choice><orig>Mad<hi rend="superscript">me</hi>..-<lb/>
                  -de Genlis</orig><reg>Madame de Genlis</reg></choice></persName> the same lady who wrote <title ref= "./Workography.xml#Theat1"> Le theatre d'<choice><orig><unclear>Edu-</unclear><lb/>
                     -cation </orig><reg>Education</reg></choice></title>which you used to be so fond of, the title<lb/>
               of it is <title ref= "./Workography.xml#Adela1">Lettres sur L'Education</title> ? if you have what<lb/>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page02.jpg"/>
               do you think of it? If you have not I think it very well<lb/>
               worth reading if you should have an opportunity -<lb/>
               <title ref= "./Workography.xml#Annal2">Les Annales de la Vertu</title> 3 vol<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> are advertized I see in the<lb/>
               last papers by the same Author - I have not yet read<lb/>
               this last work - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GenlS1">She</persName> is a very indefatigable &amp; a very<lb/>
               constant Writer for all her <del>her</del> works are on the same<lb/>
               subject - this is the least that can be said of her - the<lb/>
               rest you will judge of yourself - I was very much <choice><orig>pleas-<lb/>
               -ed </orig><reg>pleased</reg></choice>with a book I met with lately it is written by the<lb/>
               celebrated <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RaynG1">Abbe Raynal</persName> the title of it is <title ref= "./Workography.xml#Anecd1">Anecdotes<lb/>
                  historiques</title>  2 vols it contains a history of some very<lb/>
               important <unclear>Revolutions</unclear>, of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#SE">Sweden</placeName>, under <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VasaG1"><choice><orig>Gusta-<lb/>
                  -vus</orig><reg></reg></choice> Vasa</persName>, the reign of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Charl5"> Charles the fifth</persName>, the <choice><orig>conspira-<lb/>
                     -cy</orig><reg>conspiracy</reg></choice> of Fiesque in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Genoa_IT">Genoa</placeName>, the divorce between <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Henry8">Henry<lb/>
                     the Eighth</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CathA1"> Catherine</persName> when the protestant religion<lb/>
               was established in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> this is the most <hi rend="underline">un</hi>in<lb/>
               teresting part of the Work - the revolution under<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VasaG1">Gustavus Vasa</persName> &amp; the Conspiracies of Fiesque are<lb/>
               the <hi rend="underline">best</hi> part <add> of it</add> I think - I should think a very good<lb/>
             <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page03.jpg"/>   
               play might be founded <add>on</add>the conspiracy of Fiesque:<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FiesG1">the Count</persName> <del><unclear></unclear></del> is a fine, strongly marked, <choice><orig>enter<lb/>
                  -prizing</orig><reg>enterprizing</reg></choice>, ambitious, character, <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#CiboE1">his wife</persName></add> his brothers &amp; two of<lb/>
               his friends would also form good theatrical <choice><orig>cha-<lb/>
               -racters </orig><reg>characters</reg></choice>- the plot is simple &amp; the action would<lb/>
               not exceed the usual limited time of a day &amp; a night<lb/>
               If it falls in your way, I should be glad to know your<lb/>
               opinion of it - You ask me if my Italian is flown<lb/>
               over to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">Eng</placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IT">Italy</placeName> with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AmicX1"> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Amici</persName>? - I shall have <choice><orig>lei-<lb/>
               sure</orig><reg>leisure</reg></choice> to read &amp; study Italian next summer but at<lb/>
               present I shall be very glad if I preserve what I know<lb/>
               already - which in truth is very little - - -<lb/></p>
            <p>You have mentioned in several letters that you<lb/>
               were going to Balls - I have an odd question to ask you<lb/>
               Are you <hi rend="underline">happier</hi> at a Ball than anywhere else?<lb/>
               You will laugh &amp; say to be sure I <del></del>am; &amp; perhaps you<lb/>
               will ask me why I make such an uncommon <choice><orig>in-<lb/>
                  -quiry</orig><reg>inquiry</reg></choice>? I will tell you why - because I am inclined<lb/>
               to believe <del><unclear></unclear><unclear>what I have not need of my company</unclear></del><lb/>
               that it is the preparations, the <unclear>Musick</unclear>, the <unclear>dress</unclear><lb/>
             <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page04.jpg"/>  
               <add>the praise &amp;</add> the bustle which constitute the charms of a Ball - <choice><orig>there-<lb/>
                  -fore</orig><reg>therefore</reg></choice> will you my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName> favor me with<lb/>
               an exact and clear answer to this question - but I must<lb/>
               beg you to deduct the <add>Degrees of</add>pleasure which arise from all<lb/>
               the things I have mentioned; if afterwards you find that<lb/>
               you still feel pleasure which arises from none<lb/>
               of those causes I wish you would find out what<lb/>
               it arises from &amp; let me know -. our tastes do not in<lb/>
               these respects, <hi rend="underline">I believe</hi>, agree but I see the obvious<lb/>
               cause for their disagreeing - you have a very <choice><orig>agree-<lb/>
               -able</orig><reg>agreeable</reg></choice> person, agreeable manner &amp; many external<lb/>
               accomplishments which I want ; you are active<lb/>
               nimble &amp; dance well, I am awkward &amp; dance very<lb/>
               ill, it is not therefore in the least surprizing that you<lb/>
               should be happy in a ball room where you are <choice><orig>prais-<lb/>
                  -ed</orig><reg>praised</reg></choice> &amp; at least equal <add>to</add> others in those qualifications<lb/>
               which shine most in publick Assemblies or that I on<lb/>
               the contrary with every <hi rend="underline">personal</hi>disadvantage<lb/>
               &amp; others which arise from awkwardness &amp; <del></del><lb/>
             <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page05.jpg"/>  
               Mauvaise <unclear>nouse</unclear> should feel myself much less at my ease<lb/>
               in company , than amongst friends who set little<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">comparitive</hi>value on such Qualifications - <choice><orig>><hi rend="underline">compari</hi><lb/>
               -<hi rend="underline">tive</hi></orig><reg>comparative</reg></choice> value I said for because I want them myself I would<lb/>
               not depreciate them in others; I know their value; for I know<lb/>
               the want of them; &amp; the pain arising from that want is <choice><orig>cer-<lb/>
                  -tainly</orig><reg>certainly</reg></choice> the most exact measure of their worth - You know<lb/>
               I used to be laughed at for my definitions &amp; told that I<lb/>
               should sit up by a lamp like the philosophers of old; but<lb/>
               however I am not to be ridiculed out of a good thing<lb/>
               a girl of fifteen &amp; a philosopher when joined sound <choice><orig>ridi<lb/>
               -culous </orig><reg>ridiculous</reg></choice>to be sure: but if we attend to the thing &amp; not to the<del>m</del><lb/>
             <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28588_(1783_08_15)_page06.jpg"/>   
               to despise what it either <hi rend="underline">does</hi> not or <hi rend="underline">will</hi> not understand<lb/>
               I think you did not say you had seen <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BurnF1"> Miss Burney</persName> yourself<lb/>
               I wish you had for I wish very much to know what kind of<lb/>
               woman she is - Whenever you write to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Wimpole_ENK"> Wimpole S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi></placeName>. remem<lb/>
               -ber <add>me</add> to all my friends: you said <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VanX1"> Miss Van</persName> would probably be<lb/>
               gone by the time you return how comes that?- -<lb/></p>
            <p>I beg you will give my love to all the young ladies I know<lb/>
               with whom you correspond - &amp; tell them that I have not<lb/>
               forgotten them - I believe in some of your musick-<lb/>
               -books you have a song said to be written by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyttG1"> Lord <choice><orig>Little<lb/>
                  -ton</orig><reg>Littleton</reg></choice></persName> on the death of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyttL1"> his wife</persName>, if it would not be giving<lb/>
               you a great deal of trouble to copy it I should ask the<lb/>
               favor of you to send it me for I think the poetry is <choice><orig>re-<lb/>
                  -markably</orig><reg>remarkably</reg></choice> elegant &amp; I have never been able to meet<lb/>
               with it since I left <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeviE1"> M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Devis</persName>'s - the name of the<lb/>
               lady is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyttL1"> Lucy</persName> - Adieu my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName><lb/>            
            </p>
             <closer> 
               I am your's affectionately<lb/>
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
             </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back> </back>
